00:14:58,787 --> 00:15:02,883
<i>Not everyone was sure that
electric cars would save Ameica.</i>

220
00:15:03,125 --> 00:15:08,085
<i>Even as GM rolled out its first
batch of EV1's, there were skeptics.</i>

221
00:15:08,296 --> 00:15:12,323
Consumer acceptance and understanding
has been a key issue in all of this.

222
00:15:12,701 --> 00:15:17,604
And what we discovered is that people
are very cautious about the electric car.

223
00:15:17,672 --> 00:15:20,266
I would consider it, but I
haven't done enough research,

224
00:15:20,342 --> 00:15:25,279
I don't know if they're going to
be strong, big and dependable.

225
00:15:25,347 --> 00:15:27,338
I have to know where do
I have to go to recharge it,

226
00:15:27,416 --> 00:15:29,646
what do I have to do for the battery...

227
00:15:29,718 --> 00:15:35,179
People don't want a mini, tiny car
that has 15 inch wheels.

228
00:15:35,858 --> 00:15:39,327
How's he gonna fix that up and
go around town and parade it?

229
00:15:39,394 --> 00:15:43,854
<i>While some consumers expressed
skepticism about electric cars,</i>

230
00:15:43,932 --> 00:15:46,594
<i>California was pressured
to drop the mandate.</i>

231
00:15:46,668 --> 00:15:50,661
<i>A group called "Californians
against utility company abuse"</i>

232
00:15:50,739 --> 00:15:54,368
<i>fought a small utility
surcharge to build charging stations.</i>

233
00:15:54,443 --> 00:15:57,139
They would go to local city
council meetings and say:

234
00:15:57,212 --> 00:15:59,840
"You don't want to put an electric
vehicle charging station there.

235
00:15:59,915 --> 00:16:02,042
<i>"That's a waste of taxpayer money."</i>

236
00:16:02,417 --> 00:16:04,351
<i>They had this list of supporters.</i>

237
00:16:04,419 --> 00:16:07,013
Companies like Trader Joe's,
and others for which you'd say

238
00:16:07,088 --> 00:16:08,919
"Why would they
support something like this?"

239
00:16:09,057 --> 00:16:11,389
So the EV drivers got together
and started writing letters

240
00:16:11,460 --> 00:16:13,826
to some of these people that
were listed on their web site.

241
00:16:13,895 --> 00:16:17,387
as being supporters, and said
"Do you realise what you're supporting here?"

242
00:16:17,466 --> 00:16:20,264
And they got all these names
removed from the list.

243
00:16:20,402 --> 00:16:23,098
<i>Further investigation
revealed that these groups</i>

244
00:16:23,171 --> 00:16:26,265
<i>were consumer
organizations in name only</i>

245
00:16:26,408 --> 00:16:29,844
<i>funded almost
exclusively by the oil industry.</i>

246
00:16:32,814 --> 00:16:36,648
<i>Oil companies also paid for
editorials in national publications.</i>

247
00:16:38,187 --> 00:16:42,220
<i>They even argued that the
environmental benefits of EV's were dubious.</i>

248
00:16:43,291 --> 00:16:47,649
With electric vehicles we're going
to have this shift of energy away from oil.

249
00:16:47,963 --> 00:16:49,555
And if we shift it to coal,

250
00:16:49,631 --> 00:16:52,623
there are some environmental
problems that are just very disconcerting.

251
00:16:54,836 --> 00:16:57,532
<i>Right now, in the United States,
we're 55 percent coal.</i>

252
00:16:57,606 --> 00:17:00,097
If you run the numbers with
standard coal power plants,

253
00:17:00,776 --> 00:17:02,937
you don't end up with a better
environmental performance,

254
00:17:03,011 --> 00:17:04,069
but with a longer tailpipe.

255
00:17:04,145 --> 00:17:06,340
There have been numerous studies conducted

256
00:17:06,414 --> 00:17:08,575
by the California Energy Commission,

257
00:17:08,650 --> 00:17:13,212
that clearly show that electric
drive is substantially more efficient

258
00:17:13,288 --> 00:17:18,282
and less polluting, even if you get
your electricity from coal plants.

259
00:17:18,527 --> 00:17:22,395
<i>But the arguments against
electrics didn't stop there.</i>

260
00:17:22,964 --> 00:17:25,364
They even made the
ridiculous argument

261
00:17:25,433 --> 00:17:28,493
that there was an environmental
justice issue involved,

262
00:17:28,570 --> 00:17:32,904
because they said only rich
people could buy electric cars.

263
00:17:33,174 --> 00:17:38,202
<i>Well, the air doesn't know a boundary
between Brentwood and south L.A.</i>

264
00:17:38,313 --> 00:17:41,874
<i>Car companies began to argue
that the mandate was too strict.</i>

265
00:17:42,984 --> 00:17:44,542
We had to help with the regulations.

266
00:17:44,619 --> 00:17:46,951
The regulatory people knew
nothing about this stuff,

267
00:17:47,022 --> 00:17:53,621
and we began to get the eerie feeling
that we were going over a cliff.

268
00:17:54,896 --> 00:17:57,296
It wasn't going to be possible.

269
00:17:57,465 --> 00:18:00,992
California was faced with the
prospect of "What do you do

270
00:18:01,202 --> 00:18:03,534
"...if the car companies don't comply?"

271
00:18:03,972 --> 00:18:07,464
So rather than do brinksmanship

272
00:18:07,542 --> 00:18:11,137
about what would happen
if they didn't comply and stick with it,

273
00:18:11,212 --> 00:18:13,339
they started negotiating,

274
00:18:14,115 --> 00:18:18,108
a certain flexibility in the mandate.

275
00:18:18,987 --> 00:18:21,785
<i>California compromised
with the automakers</i>

276
00:18:21,856 --> 00:18:24,051
<i>adopting a memorandum of agreement.</i>

277
00:18:25,060 --> 00:18:29,628
One of the agreements with the state
was that the automakers would build

278
00:18:29,698 --> 00:18:32,724
<i>and market electric vehicles
in accordance with demand.</i>

279
00:18:32,801 --> 00:18:34,792
<i>If they didn't want to build more of them,</i>

280
00:18:34,869 --> 00:18:39,033
<i>the car companies would have to make
the case that there was no demand.</i>

281
00:18:39,307 --> 00:18:40,797
The person will go unnamed,

282
00:18:40,875 --> 00:18:45,869
but we were having a lunch in the executive
dining room at the GM tech center one day.

283
00:18:45,947 --> 00:18:48,916
Just the two of us,
and he leans over to me and says:

284
00:18:48,984 --> 00:18:52,249
"Dabels, you know something?
You are my worst enemy."

285
00:18:52,854 --> 00:18:55,015
I asked why, and he said:

286
00:18:55,090 --> 00:18:59,686
"I'm out there lobbying to show that
there's no demand for electric vehicles,

287
00:18:59,761 --> 00:19:01,854
"and you're out there proving me wrong."

288
00:19:02,330 --> 00:19:06,232
We would sit down with Hal Riney
or with executives from GM and discuss

289
00:19:06,301 --> 00:19:08,997
how fast, how far, how much.
These were the three questions we were getting.

290
00:19:09,070 --> 00:19:11,732
"Please put it in the advertising.
It's not rocket science."

291
00:19:11,806 --> 00:19:14,001
And they would go back
and do the exact opposite.

292
00:19:14,275 --> 00:19:17,142
We never saw a tv ad

293
00:19:17,212 --> 00:19:20,204
with an electric car scampering
up the side of a hill

294
00:19:20,281 --> 00:19:23,079
with a good looking man or
woman draped around it.

295
00:19:23,151 --> 00:19:25,085
That's the way they sell cars.

296
00:19:33,428 --> 00:19:35,658
<i>How does it go without gas and air?</i>

297
00:19:37,165 --> 00:19:40,726
<i>How does it go without
sparks and explosions?</i>

298
00:19:41,569 --> 00:19:45,027
<i>How does it go without
gears or transmissions?</i>

299
00:19:46,174 --> 00:19:48,802
<i>How does it go, you ask yourself?</i>

300
00:19:51,446 --> 00:19:54,040
<i>And then, you will ask;</i>

301
00:19:54,616 --> 00:19:57,551
<i>How did we go so long without it?</i>

302
00:19:58,219 --> 00:19:59,811
<i>The electric car.</i>

303
00:20:00,422 --> 00:20:01,889
<i>It isn't coming,</i>

304
00:20:03,491 --> 00:20:04,924
<i>it's here.</i>

305
00:20:10,265 --> 00:20:13,257
<i>What was the objective
of these advertisements?</i>

306
00:20:13,501 --> 00:20:17,028
<i>Was it to entice consumers
or to scare them away?</i>

307
00:20:17,706 --> 00:20:21,403
Our goal at GM was to make the full
functioning, battery electric vehicle

308
00:20:21,476 --> 00:20:24,570
a commercially viable business
opportunity for General Motors.

309
00:20:24,646 --> 00:20:29,674
<i>GM spokesman, Dave Barthmuss,
has worked for GM for nearly ten years.</i>

310
00:20:29,918 --> 00:20:34,252
We spent in excess of one billion
dollars to drive this market.

311
00:20:34,322 --> 00:20:37,485
That means award-winning
advertising, developing the vehicle,

312
00:20:37,559 --> 00:20:40,460
developing the recharging infrastructure.

313
00:20:40,528 --> 00:20:44,487
In a four-year timeframe,
from roughly 1996 to 2000,

314
00:20:44,566 --> 00:20:46,761
we were able to lease 800 EV1's.

315
00:20:46,868 --> 00:20:49,837
We started this waiting list
in order to prove demand to GM,

316
00:20:49,904 --> 00:20:52,737
but no matter how many
people we got on that list,

317
00:20:53,174 --> 00:20:56,610
that was never considered enough demand.
Everything was anecdotal to GM.

318
00:20:56,745 --> 00:20:58,872
We have heard about
these long waiting lists,

319
00:20:58,947 --> 00:21:01,916
and frankly, we did have a
list of roughly 4000 people

320
00:21:01,983 --> 00:21:05,146
that raised their hands and said:
"I would be interested in getting a new EV1

321
00:21:05,220 --> 00:21:06,710
"and being an EV1 lessee."

322
00:21:06,788 --> 00:21:10,246
We contacted each of those folks
and we riddled that list down.

323
00:21:10,325 --> 00:21:12,589
And when we got down to
a point when we were able to have

324
00:21:12,660 --> 00:21:14,457
somebody sign on the dotted line,

325
00:21:14,529 --> 00:21:17,555
that list from 4000 people
shrunk to about 50.

326
00:21:18,867 --> 00:21:22,963
<i>Only recently did they finally
admit there actually was a waiting list</i>

327
00:21:23,505 --> 00:21:25,367
<i>and tried to explain
it in the way of;</i>

328
00:21:25,440 --> 00:21:29,706
"By the time we explained all the limitations
of the car to them only 50 would sign up."

329
00:21:29,844 --> 00:21:31,937
If you sincerely want to
market a product,

330
00:21:32,013 --> 00:21:35,414
you don't start out by describing
the limitations of the product.

331
00:21:35,817 --> 00:21:39,184
<i>Tom Everhart is president
emeritus at Caltech.</i>

332
00:21:39,487 --> 00:21:42,923
<i>He served on GM's board
of directors for 13 years.</i>

333
00:21:43,291 --> 00:21:45,521
I do not think General Motors tried hard

334
00:21:46,928 --> 00:21:49,521
to get the electric cars out rapidly.

335
00:21:50,598 --> 00:21:54,295
Whether the C.E.O. of General Motors
understood that, I don't know.

336
00:21:54,402 --> 00:21:57,530
We had to ask permission of
who everyone to give a car to,

337
00:21:57,605 --> 00:22:01,905
and by the end we were low on cars,
we had to write case statements.

338
00:22:02,310 --> 00:22:04,540
<i>We tried to put the cars
in hands of celebrities,</i>

339
00:22:04,612 --> 00:22:08,571
because they were the only ones
that stood a chance of getting the car.

340
00:22:08,650 --> 00:22:11,118
The 3rd grade science teacher
didn't stand a chance.

341
00:22:11,853 --> 00:22:14,981
<i>I had to write a resume for Mel Gibson,
and what he'd done and accomplished,</i>

342
00:22:15,056 --> 00:22:18,583
because the people I was talking to
didn't believe that he warranted a car.

343
00:22:18,760 --> 00:22:20,990
I was wondering: "Why do I
have to fill this out?"

344
00:22:21,062 --> 00:22:23,360
You had to tell them where
your birthmarks were.

345
00:22:23,431 --> 00:22:25,524
I mean it was everything.

346
00:22:25,934 --> 00:22:29,233
"Have you recently had
a proctoscope inserted into your..."

347
00:22:29,304 --> 00:22:30,999
"Well, no."

348
00:22:31,606 --> 00:22:35,474
You had to get really specific
about a whole bunch of things.

349
00:22:35,810 --> 00:22:39,746
Consumers wanted it, but they
regarded it as a limited vehicle

350
00:22:39,814 --> 00:22:42,647
and they expected to
pay a limited price for it.

351
00:22:42,717 --> 00:22:46,551
And there's nothing irrational about
the consumer that said that to us.

352
00:22:46,788 --> 00:22:48,949
That's a perfectly
reasonable statement.

353
00:22:49,424 --> 00:22:52,882
"You're giving me a vehicle that
does less, I wanna pay less."

354
00:22:53,962 --> 00:22:55,020
Okay.

355
00:22:55,763 --> 00:22:58,095
But unfortunately, I
couldn't make it for less.

356
00:22:58,299 --> 00:23:01,166
They argue things like money and that
they're too expensive to build,

357
00:23:01,236 --> 00:23:05,195
yet they're building four a day.
They were very hand built cars,

358
00:23:05,273 --> 00:23:06,934
<i>with specialized components.</i>

359
00:23:07,041 --> 00:23:10,033
And had they mass-marketed them,
they of course would have come down.

360
00:23:11,346 --> 00:23:14,474
<i>As car companies made the
case there was no demand</i>

361
00:23:14,549 --> 00:23:18,246
<i>electric vehicle advocates thought
they had a sympathetic ear</i>

362
00:23:18,319 --> 00:23:22,278
<i>with the appointment of environmental
scientist, doctor Alan Lloyd</i>

363
00:23:22,357 --> 00:23:25,758
<i>as chairman of the California Air Resources Board.</i>

364
00:23:25,827 --> 00:23:29,024
First time I presided over that,

365
00:23:29,097 --> 00:23:32,999
I felt that the car companies
weren't making significant effort,

366
00:23:33,067 --> 00:23:37,868
so i felt: "Flog them harder.
Flog them often. They need to do better."

367
00:23:37,972 --> 00:23:42,136
For the regulation - we felt it needed
to be changed drastically.

368
00:23:43,511 --> 00:23:46,969
And there was some movement that way,
but it didn't go away.

369
00:23:47,048 --> 00:23:50,176
<i>While the car companies
fought the mandate in Sacramento,</i>

370
00:23:50,251 --> 00:23:54,119
<i>GM quietly closed its EV1 assembly line</i>

371
00:23:54,188 --> 00:23:56,656
<i>and began laying off its sales force.</i>

372
00:23:56,724 --> 00:24:00,717
<i>All of a sudden, we were not only taken
off the project, but taken out of the company.</i>

373
00:24:00,828 --> 00:24:02,921
They started with the
ones with the most...

374
00:24:03,197 --> 00:24:05,427
the biggest waiting lists,
and the most customers.

375
00:24:05,500 --> 00:24:08,628
The primary areas were
the ones that they dismantled first.

376
00:24:08,703 --> 00:24:10,933
And so, at the end of 2001,

377
00:24:11,005 --> 00:24:13,166
that was it in terms of my
employment with General Motors.

378
00:24:13,241 --> 00:24:15,801
Studying general Motors
practices over the years,

379
00:24:16,578 --> 00:24:18,775
and I don't speak for
the engineers and scientists

380
00:24:18,846 --> 00:24:22,475
who would really have liked to have done
a better job with motor vehicle technology,

381
00:24:22,550 --> 00:24:25,713
but the executives at the top,
their motto seemed to have been:

382
00:24:25,787 --> 00:24:27,880
"Going backwards into the future."

383
00:24:27,956 --> 00:24:30,891
And that's what they've
been doing for decades.

384
00:24:31,459 --> 00:24:35,896
<i>As a veteran consumer advocate,
Ralph Nader used grassroots campaigns</i>

385
00:24:35,964 --> 00:24:38,660
<i>to make cars safer
and more fuel efficient.</i>

386
00:24:38,933 --> 00:24:43,427
<i>He's familiar with the tactics used
by the car industry to resist change.</i>

387
00:24:44,038 --> 00:24:47,474
<i>There are all kinds of ways to take
and bring politicians to their knees.</i>

388
00:24:47,542 --> 00:24:50,306
Once the car companies
get a long delay time,

389
00:24:50,378 --> 00:24:53,176
then they go to work,
eroding, eroding.

390
00:24:53,247 --> 00:24:55,875
And than when the deadline is
approaching they say they can't do it

391
00:24:55,950 --> 00:24:58,316
and there are going to
be terrible consequences.

392
00:24:58,686 --> 00:25:01,348
<i>Automakers took
the fight to a new level.</i>

393
00:25:01,756 --> 00:25:05,157
<i>They sued
California's Air Resources Board.</i>

394
00:25:06,060 --> 00:25:11,965
<i>GM led the lawsuit, soon joined
by Chrysler and several auto dealerships.</i>

395
00:25:12,700 --> 00:25:15,362
<i>As California withered
under the pressure,</i>

396
00:25:15,436 --> 00:25:17,666
<i>the carmakers
found a powerful new ally,</i>

397
00:25:19,507 --> 00:25:21,134
<i>the federal government.</i>

398
00:25:22,276 --> 00:25:24,301
<i>Shortly after joining the suit,</i>

399
00:25:24,379 --> 00:25:27,212
<i>the Bush administration
made another announcement.</i>

400
00:25:27,281 --> 00:25:30,773
<i>Tonight, I'm proposing 1.2 billion
dollars in research funding</i>

401
00:25:31,353 --> 00:25:33,250
<i>so that America can</i>

402
00:25:33,321 --> 00:25:37,485
<i>lead the world in developing clean,
hydrogen-powered automobiles.</i>

403
00:25:40,495 --> 00:25:43,760
<i>The federal government joined
the car and oil industries</i>

404
00:25:43,831 --> 00:25:47,164
<i>to embrace a new
clean car of the future.</i>

405
00:25:47,335 --> 00:25:50,361
<i>With more than a billion
federal dollars up for grabs,</i>

406
00:25:50,805 --> 00:25:55,265
<i>over the next few years,
the campaign for hydrogen fuel cell vehicles</i>

407
00:25:55,343 --> 00:25:57,470
<i>began to sway California.</i>

408
00:25:57,712 --> 00:26:00,772
<i>Hello there and welcome
to the California Fuel Cell Partnership</i>

409
00:26:00,848 --> 00:26:05,444
