00:42:35,308 --> 00:42:37,469
We ended up rallying enough troops

651
00:42:37,544 --> 00:42:40,445
in terms of interest and
organizations to join our coalition

652
00:42:40,514 --> 00:42:45,349
<i>and then we simply didn't leave,
and stayed 24 hours a day, seven days a week.</i>

653
00:42:45,419 --> 00:42:50,482
It's 6 A.M., and I've been here
for an hour, part of a vigil.

654
00:42:50,791 --> 00:42:54,887
We're making sure that GM doesn't
sneak out their cars in the back lot.

655
00:42:55,762 --> 00:42:58,754
The first two weeks we
were pretty much ignored.

656
00:42:58,832 --> 00:43:00,265
<i>It was like monsoon rains,</i>

657
00:43:00,333 --> 00:43:02,927
<i>it was kind of depressing
to be out there,</i>

658
00:43:03,003 --> 00:43:05,267
<i>but at the same time there
was such a sense of mission.</i>

659
00:43:05,338 --> 00:43:08,501
I was here this morning
from about 5:45 A.M.,

660
00:43:08,608 --> 00:43:11,202
and it's pretty quiet.

661
00:43:13,046 --> 00:43:16,607
Finally, on day 15, we did this
announcement of this offer.

662
00:43:16,817 --> 00:43:21,049
<i>As the EV activists recorded the
VIN numbers of the cars in storage,</i>

663
00:43:21,254 --> 00:43:25,452
<i>Chelsea led a last ditch
effort to buy the cars from GM.</i>

664
00:43:25,859 --> 00:43:29,295
<i>"Okay, General Motors contends
that no one wants these EV1's here."</i>

665
00:43:29,362 --> 00:43:32,627
<i>"Would anybody be willing to buy them
for the residual price of the lease?"</i>

666
00:43:32,699 --> 00:43:36,328
<i>And within 48 hours,
over 80 people had signed up.</i>

667
00:43:36,470 --> 00:43:38,233
There were only 78 cars in that lot,

668
00:43:38,305 --> 00:43:41,672
and already we had a waiting list
for a car that wasn't available.

669
00:43:41,741 --> 00:43:44,005
It was a tremendous déjà vu moment.

670
00:43:44,077 --> 00:43:47,774
<i>At this point we thought
it would be appropriate</i>

671
00:43:47,848 --> 00:43:51,682
<i>to some full circle.
Join me in holding this check</i>

672
00:43:51,751 --> 00:43:55,585
<i>offering 1.9 million
dollars to General Motors</i>

673
00:43:55,655 --> 00:43:58,484
<i>to put these cars back on the road.</i>

674
00:44:01,695 --> 00:44:04,721
<i>Despite the offer,
GM did not respond.</i>

675
00:44:05,899 --> 00:44:09,630
<i>The fate of the last
78 EV1's remained in doubt</i>

676
00:44:10,971 --> 00:44:13,838
<i>A small group of activists
would continue their vigil,</i>

677
00:44:13,907 --> 00:44:16,467
<i>to keep the dream
of the electric car alive.</i>

678
00:44:19,346 --> 00:44:21,041
Who controls the future?

679
00:44:23,884 --> 00:44:28,446
Whoever has the biggest club.
In more ways than one.

680
00:44:29,422 --> 00:44:31,413
One they can bash you with,
and one they can belong to.

681
00:44:32,526 --> 00:44:35,185
Gentlemen! Gentlemen!

682
00:44:36,396 --> 00:44:39,456
I know you're all worried,
and I agree.

683
00:44:40,233 --> 00:44:44,863
There's plenty to be worried about.
Like this solar power plant

684
00:44:45,705 --> 00:44:48,196
already operational
outside Los Angeles.

685
00:44:49,109 --> 00:44:50,872
Photovoltaic cells,

686
00:44:51,111 --> 00:44:54,410
they converts sunlight
directly into electricity.

687
00:44:55,248 --> 00:44:59,309
Fluorescent, lasts ten times as
long as a conventional light bulb.

688
00:44:59,386 --> 00:45:01,479
uses only a quarter of the power.

689
00:45:01,821 --> 00:45:06,258
Superwindows, insulate as
well as ten sheets of glass.

690
00:45:06,693 --> 00:45:10,754
An electric car, partially
powered by solar panels.

691
00:45:11,798 --> 00:45:14,733
But the truth is, gentlemen,

692
00:45:14,834 --> 00:45:18,463
I'm not worried about
any of these things.

693
00:45:19,105 --> 00:45:22,700
Because no one is ever
going to know about them.

694
00:45:24,211 --> 00:45:28,648
There's all these conspiracy theories
out there about who killed the electric car.

695
00:45:28,715 --> 00:45:31,013
So really, who killed the electric car?

696
00:45:31,218 --> 00:45:33,743
Unfortunately, I can't
summarize that in one sentence.

697
00:45:33,820 --> 00:45:36,015
What killed the electric vehicle,

698
00:45:36,089 --> 00:45:38,319
very simply, I think,
is lack of corporate wisdom.

699
00:45:38,425 --> 00:45:41,223
In my opinion it's big oil
that killed the electric car.

700
00:45:41,294 --> 00:45:44,354
Alan Lloyd killed the electric car project.
I was there when he did it.

701
00:45:44,464 --> 00:45:47,592
The California Air Resources Board
killed the electric car

702
00:45:47,667 --> 00:45:51,103
under huge pressure
from the auto companies.

703
00:45:51,171 --> 00:45:53,298
They were an accessory
to the murder,

704
00:45:53,373 --> 00:45:56,103
but the murder was commited
by the General Motors.

705
00:45:56,309 --> 00:45:58,243
I don't believe that for a minute.

706
00:45:58,745 --> 00:46:04,911
GM would sell you a
car on pig shit if it sold.

707
00:46:10,991 --> 00:46:15,360
<i>Carmakers argue that there was not
enough demand for the electric car.</i>

708
00:46:15,428 --> 00:46:18,591
<i>Claiming to have spent millions
of dollars on advertising,</i>

709
00:46:18,665 --> 00:46:20,860
<i>they said buyers weren't interested.</i>

710
00:46:20,967 --> 00:46:24,368
<i>But did consumers even know
that the car existed?</i>

711
00:46:24,437 --> 00:46:27,372
Did you ever see this
car advertised?

712
00:46:27,440 --> 00:46:31,206
Never. That's what I'm trying to say.
It's totally under the scope of the radar.

713
00:46:31,378 --> 00:46:33,903
I don't know who drives
an EV1 actually.

714
00:46:34,147 --> 00:46:35,637
- You don't know anybody?
- Anybody.

715
00:46:35,882 --> 00:46:39,283
Maybe Fernando. I know Fernando...
Did you ever drive an EV1?

716
00:46:39,586 --> 00:46:41,850
- I've heard of them.
- He's heard of them.

717
00:46:41,955 --> 00:46:44,515
They're not making these
cars in California anymore?

718
00:46:44,591 --> 00:46:46,388
No. They're not
making them anywhere.

719
00:46:46,459 --> 00:46:48,654
That's really too bad.
We need those cars.

720
00:46:48,828 --> 00:46:50,955
Why are they getting rid of it?

721
00:46:52,565 --> 00:46:55,432
They said that there was
no demand for the car.

722
00:46:55,502 --> 00:46:56,867
Are they insane?

723
00:46:57,170 --> 00:46:58,762
That's a no-brainer.
Of course there's a demand.

724
00:46:58,838 --> 00:47:02,137
Save gas, save people, save air,
save oxygen, save the world.

725
00:47:02,208 --> 00:47:03,800
All sounds good to me.

726
00:47:06,579 --> 00:47:09,104
<i>We've been selling
vehicles for a century,</i>

727
00:47:09,215 --> 00:47:12,810
<i>and as you might imagine,
we've figured out what people wanted.</i>

728
00:47:12,886 --> 00:47:15,980
If you ask them, they say:
"I want a 300 mile range."

729
00:47:16,056 --> 00:47:19,389
<i>"I want to be able
to go 85 or 90 mph</i>

730
00:47:19,459 --> 00:47:22,622
<i>"I want to carry four passengers
and have a big trunk. "</i>

731
00:47:23,129 --> 00:47:25,859
Which is basically
what we were already selling.

732
00:47:25,932 --> 00:47:27,559
<i>I've said this
time and time again.</i>

733
00:47:27,634 --> 00:47:29,829
<i>People will buy anthing
you convince them to buy.</i>

734
00:47:31,004 --> 00:47:35,373
Feed people enough, and
they believe that's a diet.

735
00:47:36,476 --> 00:47:38,876
Consumers, they
couldn't see the difference

736
00:47:38,945 --> 00:47:41,175
between electric car and
the car they're already driving

737
00:47:41,247 --> 00:47:43,738
because they don't
read environmental impact.

738
00:47:44,384 --> 00:47:46,818
They don't read political instability
caused by oil production

739
00:47:46,886 --> 00:47:47,910
in the Middle East.

740
00:47:47,987 --> 00:47:51,582
All they read is does this car
work and how much does it cost.

741
00:47:52,992 --> 00:47:55,825
<i>What really killed EV's,
is American consumers</i>

742
00:47:55,895 --> 00:47:59,558
because they did not accept this
idea, did not embrace it,

743
00:48:00,000 --> 00:48:03,631
that vehicles could have
these limited ranges

744
00:48:03,703 --> 00:48:06,103
and still be functional,
useful, practical.

745
00:48:12,412 --> 00:48:16,041
<i>Did the electric car die
because of the battery technology ?</i>

746
00:48:16,116 --> 00:48:18,846
<i>Did EV's really not
have enough range?</i>

747
00:48:18,918 --> 00:48:22,251
<i>Did car companies use
the best batteries available?</i>

748
00:48:22,322 --> 00:48:26,281
<i>Battery technology at that
time was lead accid batteries</i>

749
00:48:26,359 --> 00:48:29,021
<i>and allowed the car to go 60 miles.</i>

750
00:48:29,195 --> 00:48:33,553
If you started out on a trip knowing
that you were going to go dead in 60 miles,

751
00:48:33,867 --> 00:48:35,858
you'd be nervous about
making the trip.

752
00:48:37,003 --> 00:48:40,029
<i>People think that they need
a car that will go 300 miles</i>

753
00:48:40,106 --> 00:48:43,405
and be able to charge it up
or refuel it in five minutes.

754
00:48:43,643 --> 00:48:48,335
<i>For virtually 90-95% of your driving,
you really don't need that.</i>

755
00:48:48,648 --> 00:48:51,549
You need a vehicle that will go
at least 60 miles or so,

756
00:48:51,618 --> 00:48:54,610
and that way your daily
commute is covered.

757
00:48:54,687 --> 00:48:59,147
<i>For those who wanted greater
range from an EV, a 100 miles or more</i>

758
00:48:59,225 --> 00:49:01,489
<i>a better battery already existed.</i>

759
00:49:01,561 --> 00:49:04,894
<i>Developed by a well known
inventor working in Troy, Michigan,</i>

760
00:49:04,964 --> 00:49:07,558
<i>about 30 miles from
General Motors headquarters.</i>

761
00:49:07,700 --> 00:49:11,602
- I'm Stan and...
- And lris Ovshinsky.

762
00:49:12,472 --> 00:49:13,734
I think you shouldn't do that.

763
00:49:13,807 --> 00:49:16,742
You should say you're Stan Ovshinsky,
and I'll say I'm Iris Ovshinsky.

764
00:49:16,810 --> 00:49:18,402
Don't do that. It's funny.

765
00:49:18,478 --> 00:49:23,677
<i>With over 200 patents to his name,
Stan Ovshinsky had pioneered a new battery</i>

766
00:49:23,750 --> 00:49:26,776
<i>and GM purchased
controlling share of his company.</i>

767
00:49:27,020 --> 00:49:31,286
We were chosen over
60 different big companies,

768
00:49:31,458 --> 00:49:33,119
like Westinghouse and others,

769
00:49:33,293 --> 00:49:37,389
who wanted to win the
race to make the batteries

770
00:49:37,764 --> 00:49:41,359
that would be used in pure electric cars.

771
00:49:41,868 --> 00:49:44,837
And we were chosen
because we had a battery.

772
00:49:45,438 --> 00:49:49,772
<i>And to us,
putting it into a car</i>

773
00:49:49,843 --> 00:49:52,505
<i>was not the most
gigantic thing.</i>

774
00:49:52,712 --> 00:49:54,441
What were we supposed to do?

775
00:49:54,514 --> 00:49:56,641
But you did expect
champagne and roses.

776
00:49:56,716 --> 00:49:58,741
I expected
champagne and roses.

777
00:49:59,419 --> 00:50:03,583
When I said that we were going to
put a paragraph into a newspaper,

778
00:50:03,656 --> 00:50:05,317
that said we had achieved this,

779
00:50:05,391 --> 00:50:09,054
I really expected
congratulations to flow in.

780
00:50:09,429 --> 00:50:13,388
And then I knew that something was
different when the opposite happened.

781
00:50:13,466 --> 00:50:18,130
<i>Ovshinsky was censored for publicizing
his battery advances without permission</i>

782
00:50:19,272 --> 00:50:22,639
<i>and asked not to run
advertising in national publications.</i>

783
00:50:23,409 --> 00:50:26,310
<i>The EV1 debuted
with a weaker battery.</i>

784
00:50:26,546 --> 00:50:29,344
<i>It would be another 2 years
before Ovshinsky's batteries</i>

785
00:50:29,415 --> 00:50:31,178
<i>were installed in the EV1.</i>

786
00:50:32,719 --> 00:50:36,348
The first version of the EV1
had defective Delco batteries,

787
00:50:36,422 --> 00:50:37,616
and they kept failing.

788
00:50:37,690 --> 00:50:40,181
That was GM's failure,
on those batteries.

789
00:50:40,260 --> 00:50:42,854
Once they put good batteries in,
they didn't have any problems.

790
00:50:42,962 --> 00:50:46,625
<i>Ultimately, GM sold its
share in Ovshinsky's company</i>

791
00:50:46,699 --> 00:50:48,394
<i>to an unlikely buyer.</i>

792
00:50:48,668 --> 00:50:51,102
<i>Then, when the Ni-MH
batteries were improved,</i>

793
00:50:51,170 --> 00:50:55,903
so that they're now lasting longer than
the life of the car and cheaper than an engine,

794
00:50:56,576 --> 00:51:01,673
Chevron Texaco stepped in and
purchased control from General Motors

795
00:51:01,748 --> 00:51:03,645
<i>of Ovshinsky technology.</i>

796
00:51:04,617 --> 00:51:07,450
<i>The oil companies do not feel
threatened by battery technology,</i>

797
00:51:08,621 --> 00:51:10,418
because they
effectively crushed it.

798
00:51:10,490 --> 00:51:12,685
The electric car is an
interesting case study.

799
00:51:12,759 --> 00:51:15,793
It was such an abysmal failure,

800
00:51:16,129 --> 00:51:18,825
that there are a lot of people
involved in the initial decision making

801
00:51:18,898 --> 00:51:21,958
that are pointing fingers
at whose responsibility it is.

802
00:51:32,378 --> 00:51:37,111
<i>To Basrah and all of Iraq comes good
news with the opening of a new oil field.</i>

803
00:51:37,183 --> 00:51:41,210
<i>The pipeline runs across the
desert to the Persian Gulf at Al Faw.</i>

804
00:51:41,988 --> 00:51:46,220
<i>There, tankers load up with the
precious fuel the world needs so badly.</i>

805
00:51:46,960 --> 00:51:51,021
<i>Yes, it's a big day for Iraq,
and there's a feast to celebrate.</i>

806
00:51:51,431 --> 00:51:54,559
<i>Sheep stuffed with rice
and host of other good things.</i>

807
00:51:55,101 --> 00:51:59,765
<i>But that's only the first of the good
things that will come to Iraq, thanks to oil.</i>

808
00:52:02,141 --> 00:52:04,974
<i>Oil companies have rarely
shied away from global issues.</i>

809
00:52:05,044 --> 00:52:08,502
<i>But why did they lobby so
hard to build a public opposition</i>

810
00:52:08,581 --> 00:52:10,606
<i>to the electric car in California?</i>

811
00:52:10,683 --> 00:52:13,277
I find it difficult to rationalize

812
00:52:15,188 --> 00:52:17,884
why the oil industry got so
intimately involved in this.

813
00:52:17,957 --> 00:52:21,324
Other than maybe
they saw it as a threat

814
00:52:21,394 --> 00:52:25,797
to the monopoly they had on
providing the transportation fuel.

815
00:52:25,932 --> 00:52:29,999
There's no question that the oil companies
who control the market today

816
00:52:31,304 --> 00:52:34,398
have a strong incentive
to discourage alternatives,

817
00:52:34,974 --> 00:52:38,000
except the alternatives
that they themselves control.

818
00:52:38,144 --> 00:52:41,204
Just as General Motors,

819
00:52:42,582 --> 00:52:46,279
<i>40 or 50 years ago, bought up
the trolley systems and shut them down,</i>

820
00:52:46,352 --> 00:52:51,915
<i>the oil companies have opposed
the creation of an electric infrastructure.</i>

821
00:52:53,826 --> 00:52:57,284
I differ strongly with that.
We did not kill the electric car.

822
00:52:57,363 --> 00:52:59,126
The petroleum industry
did not kill the electric car.

823
00:52:59,198 --> 00:53:02,258
<i>What killed the electric car
was antiquated technology.</i>

824
00:53:02,702 --> 00:53:06,001
It's a good example of
something we should not repeat,

825
00:53:06,072 --> 00:53:07,937
an example we need to avoid.

826
00:53:11,477 --> 00:53:15,709
<i>There's still roughly a trillion barrels
worth of oil in the Earth's crust.</i>

827
00:53:16,082 --> 00:53:20,985
And if you figure that the average price
of that subsequent oil will be 100 $ a barrel,

828
00:53:21,054 --> 00:53:24,751
that's a 100 trillion dollars
worth of business yet to be done.

829
00:53:26,793 --> 00:53:30,820
<i>However, at some point when
an alternative is good enough,</i>

830
00:53:30,897 --> 00:53:35,630
<i>people will snap over, and that's
what the oil companies fear the most.</i>

831
00:53:36,269 --> 00:53:39,466
<i>We use 180 million gallons
of gasoline a week in California.</i>

832
00:53:39,539 --> 00:53:44,340
Right now, the price is 2,20 $.
A year ago, it was 1,20 $.

833
00:53:44,510 --> 00:53:46,410
There's a dollar more a gallon.

834
00:53:46,479 --> 00:53:50,677
Somebody's making 180
million dollars more a week.

835
00:53:50,750 --> 00:53:54,151
<i>It's the same gas, the same
pipeline, the same refinery.</i>

836
00:53:54,220 --> 00:53:56,085
The profits are outstanding.

837
00:54:04,264 --> 00:54:06,859
<i>What the oil companies feared,</i>

838
00:54:06,933 --> 00:54:11,666
is that electric vehicles would
become successful six years from now.

839
00:54:11,738 --> 00:54:13,968
What the automobile
companies feared,

840
00:54:14,040 --> 00:54:17,134
was that they'd be losing money
on electric vehicles in the next six months.

841
00:54:23,583 --> 00:54:28,111
<i>Even as car companies made electric
cars, they fought them at every step.</i>

842
00:54:28,387 --> 00:54:29,820
<i>What was their motive?</i>

843
00:54:29,889 --> 00:54:32,983
<i>Why were they so determined
to take them off the road?</i>

844
00:54:33,426 --> 00:54:35,394
I think in the beginning,

845
00:54:35,461 --> 00:54:37,827
General Motors didn't believe
the car would catch on.

846
00:54:37,897 --> 00:54:40,422
I don't think they'd thought
they'd ever have to worry about

847
00:54:40,500 --> 00:54:44,402
something like a conspiracy to keep it
from happening. They hated the mandate.

848
00:54:44,470 --> 00:54:47,132
They hated it so much that they
ended up not really wanting

849
00:54:47,206 --> 00:54:48,639
to be in the business of EV's.

850
00:54:48,708 --> 00:54:53,475
What I detected was a huge
resentment about being told

851
00:54:53,579 --> 00:54:56,139
<i>what type of motor
vehicle had to be made.</i>

852
00:54:56,215 --> 00:55:00,743
<i>And it became a fight of
principle rather than one of trying</i>

853
00:55:00,820 --> 00:55:03,721
to technologically
solve the problem.

854
00:55:04,056 --> 00:55:08,425
I do know that I was surprised
at some of the stances they took

855
00:55:08,494 --> 00:55:11,156
in Sacramento in arguing.

856
00:55:13,666 --> 00:55:15,224
End of comment.

857
00:55:17,069 --> 00:55:20,232
<i>In a confidential 1995 memo</i>

858
00:55:20,306 --> 00:55:23,742
<i>the American Automobile
Manufacturers Association</i>

859
00:55:23,810 --> 00:55:27,473
<i>sought to hire a PR firm
to manage a so-called </i>

860
00:55:27,547 --> 00:55:30,380
<i>"grassroots and educational campaign"</i>

861
00:55:30,583 --> 00:55:33,416
<i>to create a climate
to repeal the mandate.</i>

862
00:55:33,786 --> 00:55:35,981
<i>The challenge,
according to the document,</i>

863
00:55:36,055 --> 00:55:39,616
<i>was "greater consumer
acceptance of electric vehicles."</i>

864
00:55:40,359 --> 00:55:45,126
<i>Why would the car companies campaign
so hard against their own creation?</i>

865
00:55:45,398 --> 00:55:48,799
I made the case at the
General Motors board,

866
00:55:49,769 --> 00:55:53,899
that the reason for the EV1
was to give General Motors

867
00:55:53,973 --> 00:55:58,774
<i>a very big head start
in how you transform electricity</i>

868
00:55:58,845 --> 00:56:01,370
<i>into the drive power of a car.</i>

869
00:56:01,447 --> 00:56:04,712
And we give them two or three years lead,

870
00:56:04,784 --> 00:56:07,082
and in my judgement it did.

871
00:56:07,220 --> 00:56:10,656
<i>But my frustration was
they didn't capitalize on the lead.</i>

872
00:56:10,857 --> 00:56:13,917
<i>And the reason, which
was discussed with the board,</i>

873
00:56:14,126 --> 00:56:18,859
was that there was not a
profit seemed to be coming out

874
00:56:19,031 --> 00:56:21,556
<i>of either electric cars or hybrids.</i>

875
00:56:21,801 --> 00:56:26,295
<i>They could not understand how
Toyota could possibly make a profit</i>

876
00:56:26,372 --> 00:56:30,138
<i>out of the Prius, for example.
They were gonna lose their shirt.</i>

877
00:56:30,676 --> 00:56:35,510
<i>And as evidence have shown,
I don't think Toyota is losing their shirt.</i>

878
00:56:36,382 --> 00:56:39,078
<i>If loss of revenue
worried car companies</i>

879
00:56:39,218 --> 00:56:42,847
<i>than the electric car posed
another problem altogether:</i>

880
00:56:42,922 --> 00:56:47,859
<i>it had no internal combustion engine,
the cornerstone of the auto industry.</i>

881
00:56:48,594 --> 00:56:50,994
These parts represent a large
part of a dealership's income,

882
00:56:52,131 --> 00:56:55,132
through the replacement
and the maintenance.

883
00:56:55,234 --> 00:56:59,102
Esentially, this group of parts
is a visual representation

884
00:56:59,171 --> 00:57:02,663
of the profits the auto industry
doesn't make when they sell an EV1,

885
00:57:02,742 --> 00:57:04,232
or an EV in general.

886
00:57:04,310 --> 00:57:08,576
I can actually identify a lot of these
that didn't get used on the EV1 program.

887
00:57:08,648 --> 00:57:10,616
<i>Oil filters you need
four times a year.</i>

888
00:57:10,683 --> 00:57:11,980
<i>It was the most prominent thing,</i>

889
00:57:12,051 --> 00:57:14,781
<i>along with several
quarts of oil every time.</i>

890
00:57:14,987 --> 00:57:17,615
I didn't enjoy working on the
internal combustion engines,

891
00:57:17,690 --> 00:57:19,555
just due to the fact
you got so dirty.

892
00:57:19,625 --> 00:57:23,288
And working on the EV1, I
basically go home looking like this.

893
00:57:24,497 --> 00:57:27,898
<i>Servicing the EV1 was pretty simple.</i>

894
00:57:27,967 --> 00:57:31,061
It came in about every 5000 miles.

895
00:57:31,137 --> 00:57:36,973
We'd rotate the tires, add washer fluid
to it, and send it back out on the street.

896
00:57:38,244 --> 00:57:42,010
It's amazing. Look how dirty
I've gotten just handling this stuff.

897
00:57:42,415 --> 00:57:43,541
It's kind of sad.

898
00:57:43,616 --> 00:57:45,641
<i>In order to sincerely
market a clean car,</i>

899
00:57:45,718 --> 00:57:48,812
you have to suggest
that your core product is dirty,

900
00:57:48,955 --> 00:57:51,253
that it uses oil, that it uses gas,

901
00:57:51,324 --> 00:57:53,884
and that increases our
dependance on foreign oil.

902
00:57:53,960 --> 00:57:55,257
And here's this
product that doesn't.

903
00:57:55,528 --> 00:57:58,793
It looks very schizophrenic,
but I think, when it started...

904
00:57:58,864 --> 00:58:01,230
"We can show the people in California

905
00:58:01,300 --> 00:58:05,066
we can meet the zero
emission requirements."

906
00:58:05,271 --> 00:58:08,468
And later on: "Do we
want to show them?"

907
00:58:08,541 --> 00:58:10,168
"That means, all of
our other cars..."

908
00:58:10,409 --> 00:58:13,276
But the more it caught on, the more
that there was this dichotomy

909
00:58:13,346 --> 00:58:18,716
between clean and efficient and
non-polluting versus a Suburban.

910
00:58:19,552 --> 00:58:21,713
<i>Car companies
had convinced themselves</i>

911
00:58:21,787 --> 00:58:25,518
<i>that they couldn't make money
in the short term with the electric car.</i>

912
00:58:25,591 --> 00:58:29,789
<i>In order to do that, they would
need an entirely different vehicle.</i>

913
00:58:30,296 --> 00:58:33,356
<i>General Motors made a
commitment to the Hummer,</i>

914
00:58:33,566 --> 00:58:36,694
because they could see that
the Hummer would make them money.

915
00:58:40,106 --> 00:58:43,166
When SUV's first came out,
people said: "I can't drive that."

916
00:58:43,242 --> 00:58:45,301
- "That big old truck?"
- Especially for the ladies.

917
00:58:45,378 --> 00:58:47,403
- "I can't see out of there."
- "I'm going to murder somebody in that."

918
00:58:47,480 --> 00:58:50,176
- "That's too big."
- "That's too big for me."

919
00:58:50,249 --> 00:58:53,412
- But they convinced people. "This is safer."
- "You need this car."

920
00:58:53,486 --> 00:58:55,420
- "You need a big car."
- "This is a safe car."

921
00:58:55,488 --> 00:58:57,046
- "You need this for your family."
- "Bigger, safer."

922
00:58:57,123 --> 00:59:03,187
The idea of a penny-pinching EV1
that was super-green,

923
00:59:03,262 --> 00:59:04,695
that didn't get a lot attraction.

924
00:59:04,764 --> 00:59:08,222
Whereas the idea of a gigantic SUV

925
00:59:08,300 --> 00:59:11,565
that would crush your neighbor,
that did get a lot attraction.

926
00:59:11,637 --> 00:59:14,470
<i>Basically, that tells us
what the 90's was about.</i>

927
00:59:16,142 --> 00:59:21,580
<i>What began as a 25 000 $ tax
break, grew to a 100 000 $</i>

928
00:59:21,747 --> 00:59:25,945
<i>when Congress passed the President's
economic stimulus package last spring.</i>

929
00:59:26,085 --> 00:59:28,850
We think small businesses need
to have support at this time

930
00:59:29,121 --> 00:59:31,487
to keep them afloat, to
keep the economy moving ahead.

931
00:59:31,590 --> 00:59:34,184
But there's an encouragement
for the small business person,

932
00:59:34,260 --> 00:59:37,889
not just to stay afloat, but to go
the biggest gas guzzler there is.

933
00:59:37,963 --> 00:59:42,093
The 6,000-pound car, the biggest.
Does that make sense?

934
00:59:42,301 --> 00:59:46,135
I don't think we can dictate
what vehicles people buy.

935
00:59:46,205 --> 00:59:48,173
- The goal here is...
- This is encouraging them!

936
00:59:48,240 --> 00:59:50,834
You can almost buy the
whole car for the tax break.

937
00:59:50,910 --> 00:59:53,470
I'm not going to concede

938
00:59:53,546 --> 00:59:56,106
that that would be the
way that this would be used...

939
00:59:56,182 --> 00:59:58,013
There is some evidence that
is how they are being used.

940
00:59:58,084 --> 01:00:00,211
I don't know. We'll have
to wait and see what happens.

941
01:00:39,525 --> 01:00:43,086
I don't want to see Hummers driven
off the market by the government.

942
01:00:43,529 --> 01:00:47,863
I want to see everything given
a level, equal chance.

943
01:00:47,933 --> 01:00:51,960
The thing that bothers me is that
it's not a level, equal chance.

944
01:00:52,037 --> 01:00:54,870
We're using our military
to ensure the flow of oil.

945
01:00:54,940 --> 01:00:58,933
We're using tax dollars to support
the car companies in different ways,

946
01:00:59,011 --> 01:01:03,607
and we're not using our tax money to do
the things that we really need to do

947
01:01:03,682 --> 01:01:04,950
to prepare for the future.

948
01:01:11,757 --> 01:01:16,285
<i>Federal policy has always had
tremendous power to shape the future.</i>

949
01:01:16,762 --> 01:01:20,129
<i>As it gave enormous
incentives to buy SUV's</i>

950
01:01:20,199 --> 01:01:24,898
<i>the federal government also sued
California to stop the electric car.</i>

951
01:01:25,571 --> 01:01:29,863
<i>Some pointed to the influence
of the oil and auto industries.</i>

952
01:01:30,843 --> 01:01:34,507
<i>They control things in Washington,
they and the automobile industry.</i>

953
01:01:35,881 --> 01:01:37,542
<i>Now they've got Andy Card there,</i>

954
01:01:37,616 --> 01:01:41,643
<i>former lobbyist, as chief
of staff in the White House.</i>

955
01:01:41,720 --> 01:01:44,689
I guess they don't have to
pay the lobbyists anymore.

956
01:01:44,757 --> 01:01:46,588
So they're saving a little money there.

957
01:01:46,792 --> 01:01:48,851
<i>Andrew Card was chief of staff</i>

958
01:01:48,928 --> 01:01:52,523
<i>when the Bush administration
joined the suit against California.</i>

959
01:01:52,831 --> 01:01:55,629
<i>Card had also been
president and C.E.O.</i>

960
01:01:55,701 --> 01:01:59,262
<i>of the American Automobile
Manufacturers Association</i>

961
01:01:59,338 --> 01:02:03,536
<i>during its campaign to kill
California's electric car mandate.</i>

962
01:02:04,009 --> 01:02:08,446
Industries began to see if we
don't kill this cancer in California,

963
01:02:08,514 --> 01:02:10,505
<i>it's going to spread to
the rest of the country.</i>

964
01:02:10,583 --> 01:02:14,849
<i>I think it became a strategy
on the part of many companies</i>

965
01:02:14,920 --> 01:02:17,150
<i>to make it a national issue.</i>

966
01:02:17,256 --> 01:02:19,850
I was even told once by a very
prominent congressman

967
01:02:19,925 --> 01:02:21,722
who I shall not mention
by name, that

968
01:02:21,794 --> 01:02:26,595
"I could understand and tolerate
what you're doing in California,

969
01:02:26,699 --> 01:02:30,465
"but if you ever try to spread
your California program"

970
01:02:30,536 --> 01:02:34,131
"to the rest of my country,
I'm going to have to do battle with you."

971
01:02:35,307 --> 01:02:38,640
Sometimes, I listen
to the energy debate

972
01:02:38,711 --> 01:02:43,648
and I think I'm watching an old
movie that was made back in the 70's.

973
01:02:43,849 --> 01:02:50,550
Because the discussion is exactly
the same as it was 30 years ago.

974
01:02:50,923 --> 01:02:53,983
<i>Our average vehicle,
average car on the road,</i>

975
01:02:54,059 --> 01:02:56,584
<i>is less efficient than
it was 20 years ago.</i>

976
01:02:56,829 --> 01:02:59,161
And this is just a complete
abdication of leadership.

977
01:02:59,231 --> 01:03:01,096
Political leadership, really.

978
01:03:01,467 --> 01:03:06,302
Because it's impossible to get fuel economy
standards passed through the U.S. Congress.

979
01:03:08,540 --> 01:03:11,976
<i>After the OPEC
oil embargo in the 1970's,</i>

980
01:03:12,044 --> 01:03:15,844
<i>the U.S. government created
Corporate Average Fuel Economy</i>

981
01:03:15,914 --> 01:03:20,582
<i>or CAFE standards, to improve
fuel economy in American vehicles.</i>

982
01:03:20,986 --> 01:03:27,289
<i>As a result, in less than 10 years, fuel
economy increased by more than 50 percent.</i>

983
01:03:27,559 --> 01:03:31,996
<i>Unfortunately, two decades later,
there has been virtually no change.</i>

984
01:03:32,064 --> 01:03:34,259
Jimmy Carter was the last president

985
01:03:34,333 --> 01:03:38,895
that really made
energy a high priority.

986
01:03:38,971 --> 01:03:43,806
He devoted his first 90 days in office
to put together an energy plan.

987
01:03:44,310 --> 01:03:46,107
I was there as part of it.

988
01:03:46,345 --> 01:03:49,837
No president since then
has put that kind of effort into it.

989
01:03:50,182 --> 01:03:55,551
I am tonight setting a clear goal for
the energy policy of the United States.

990
01:03:56,121 --> 01:04:00,182
Beginning this moment, this
nation will never use

991
01:04:00,259 --> 01:04:05,754
more foreign oil than
we did in 1977. Never.

992
01:04:14,506 --> 01:04:18,704
<i>There was a radical change
when Ronald Reagan came in</i>

993
01:04:18,777 --> 01:04:23,476
<i>and took down the solar panels off the
White House roof that Jimmy had put up,</i>

994
01:04:23,549 --> 01:04:26,609
and esentially, declared
war on the sun.

995
01:04:26,685 --> 01:04:30,684
I've put a freeze on pending
regulations and set up a task force

996
01:04:31,123 --> 01:04:34,149
under vice president Bush
to review regulations

997
01:04:34,226 --> 01:04:36,922
with an eye toward getting
rid of as many as possible.

998
01:04:37,196 --> 01:04:40,996
I have de-controlled oil, which should
result in more domestic production

999
01:04:41,066 --> 01:04:43,193
and less dependance
on foreign oil.

1000
01:04:43,268 --> 01:04:46,795
When Reagan came in, he was not
a supporter of fuel economy,

1001
01:04:46,872 --> 01:04:49,238
of conservation,
of renewables.

1002
01:04:49,475 --> 01:04:53,343
In the mid 1980's, he basically
stopped any improvement

1003
01:04:53,412 --> 01:04:55,744
in fuel economy
standards for cars.

1004
01:04:55,948 --> 01:04:58,610
And then, in 1985,
the prices of oil collapsed.

1005
01:04:59,051 --> 01:05:03,314
I would not lay all of the blame
at Ronald Reagan's feet, by any means.

1006
01:05:04,456 --> 01:05:08,017
I think he had his share of
responsibility, but so did the Saudis,

1007
01:05:08,260 --> 01:05:11,718
who made a very
calculating decision,

1008
01:05:12,297 --> 01:05:14,731
to drop the price
of oil dramatically,

1009
01:05:15,434 --> 01:05:19,336
<i>principally to ensure that
none of these alternative fuels</i>

1010
01:05:20,539 --> 01:05:26,569
<i>and energy saving measures
really produced the desired results.</i>

1011
01:05:27,246 --> 01:05:31,876
<i>So they kept the junkie
hooked up, in other words.</i>

1012
01:05:31,950 --> 01:05:37,479
<i>And as a result, we are
today still addicted to oil.</i>

1013
01:05:39,358 --> 01:05:41,656
When Clinton came in,
and I worked for Clinton,

1014
01:05:41,727 --> 01:05:46,391
we were definitely quite interested
in trying to come up with alternatives

1015
01:05:46,465 --> 01:05:48,490
and improve the fuel
economy of the fleet.

1016
01:05:48,567 --> 01:05:51,468
<i>Politically, it was still very unattractive.</i>

1017
01:05:51,570 --> 01:05:54,004
<i>The automobile lobby
was quite powerful then,</i>

1018
01:05:54,072 --> 01:05:57,940
<i>so the administration kind of made
a bargain with the automobile companies,</i>

1019
01:05:58,010 --> 01:06:00,672
<i>this partnership for
new generation of vehicles</i>

1020
01:06:00,746 --> 01:06:02,737
<i>where we would develop
hybrid vehicles,</i>

1021
01:06:02,815 --> 01:06:06,114
<i>a combination of a gasoline
engine and an electric drive train.</i>

1022
01:06:06,218 --> 01:06:09,654
<i>In return, we wouldn't really
pursue fuel economy standards.</i>

1023
01:06:10,322 --> 01:06:12,654
I've never met a five year
old kid like this in my life.

1024
01:06:12,724 --> 01:06:15,693
He said: "I'm glad
to meet you, Mr. President."

1025
01:06:15,761 --> 01:06:19,356
"I want you to make a car that runs
on electricity and doesn't pollute the air."

1026
01:06:20,766 --> 01:06:22,893
I was so impressed,
I went to get Al Gore

1027
01:06:22,968 --> 01:06:24,697
and I introduced him
to this five year old boy,

1028
01:06:24,770 --> 01:06:29,469
and he said: "Hello, Mr. vice président.
I intend to spend my life working on this."

1029
01:06:29,541 --> 01:06:32,510
"I am going to help you
develop an electric car"

1030
01:06:32,578 --> 01:06:34,273
"that has no pollution."

1031
01:06:34,580 --> 01:06:37,811
Al Gore says: "That means
we're going to be partners."

1032
01:06:37,883 --> 01:06:39,441
He said: "Yes, I guess so."

1033
01:06:39,518 --> 01:06:42,578
"But you don't understand. I'm
going to spend my whole life on this."

1034
01:06:46,925 --> 01:06:51,157
For 8-9 years, we've spent about
a billion dollars of taxpayers' money

1035
01:06:51,230 --> 01:06:53,027
to develop hybrid vehicles.

1036
01:06:53,632 --> 01:06:58,660
Ironically, the U.S. car companies
didn't put any hybrids on the road.

1037
01:06:58,737 --> 01:07:01,399
<i>In fact, the minute George Bush
got elected president,</i>

1038
01:07:01,473 --> 01:07:04,033
<i>the U.S. car companies
walked away from hybrids.</i>

1039
01:07:04,109 --> 01:07:06,441
But, and this is the irony,

1040
01:07:06,512 --> 01:07:09,879
the U.S. program got the
Japanese very nervous.

1041
01:07:09,948 --> 01:07:14,385
So Toyota and Honda, in
response, developed hybrids,

1042
01:07:14,553 --> 01:07:16,714
because they didn't
want to be beaten by the U.S.

1043
01:07:23,295 --> 01:07:26,662
Now, they lure people into
thinking they're doing something

1044
01:07:26,732 --> 01:07:28,893
but they sweet-talk.

1045
01:07:28,967 --> 01:07:32,427
I remember way back we
used to have this joke,

1046
01:07:32,671 --> 01:07:34,502
<i>but it's not a joke anymore.</i>

1047
01:07:34,573 --> 01:07:38,031
<i>We're giving the environmentalists
the music and the industry the action.</i>

1048
01:07:38,110 --> 01:07:41,238
<i>The second step toward making
America less dependant on foreign oil</i>

1049
01:07:41,313 --> 01:07:44,305
<i>is to produce and refine
more crude oil here at home</i>

1050
01:07:44,383 --> 01:07:46,977
<i>in environmentally
sensitive ways.</i>

1051
01:07:48,453 --> 01:07:50,717
<i>By far the most promising
site for oil in America</i>

1052
01:07:50,789 --> 01:07:54,122
<i>is the Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge in Alaska.</i>

1053
01:07:59,898 --> 01:08:04,028
<i>While it is predicted that
the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge</i>

1054
01:08:04,102 --> 01:08:08,732
<i>could supply America with slightly
more than one year's supply of oil,</i>

1055
01:08:09,107 --> 01:08:13,567
<i>simply raising fuel economy
standards to 40 miles per gallon</i>

1056
01:08:13,645 --> 01:08:17,672
<i>could save the same
amount of fuel within 15 years.</i>

1057
01:08:25,824 --> 01:08:29,760
<i>The oil industry and
the automobile companies</i>

1058
01:08:29,828 --> 01:08:31,489
<i>are resistant to change.</i>

1059
01:08:31,563 --> 01:08:36,398
The American people need to be reminded
that it took a law to get seatbelts in the cars.

1060
01:08:36,568 --> 01:08:39,002
It took a law to get airbags in the cars.

1061
01:08:39,071 --> 01:08:43,371
It took a law to get the mileage up
from 12 to 20 miles per gallon.

1062
01:08:43,442 --> 01:08:47,105
<i>It took a law to get catalytic
converters to control the pollution.</i>

1063
01:08:47,512 --> 01:08:51,471
I think clean cars are too important
to be left to the automobile industry.

1064
01:08:58,991 --> 01:09:03,485
<i>The California mandate forced
automakers to make electric cars.</i>

1065
01:09:03,695 --> 01:09:07,222
<i>When California changed it,
the cars vanished.</i>

1066
01:09:07,833 --> 01:09:12,236
<i>Why did California retreat
from the bold law it created?</i>

1067
01:09:12,704 --> 01:09:15,537
Having visited all the car
companies, they were saying:

1068
01:09:15,807 --> 01:09:19,607
"Look, we can't produce
these increasing numbers of the

1069
01:09:19,678 --> 01:09:21,646
<i>battery electric vehicles."</i>

1070
01:09:21,713 --> 01:09:23,908
<i>And I became convinced that...</i>

1071
01:09:24,583 --> 01:09:27,916
What are we supposed to do here?
Is our job to clean the air?

1072
01:09:27,986 --> 01:09:33,083
Or is it to force a certain number of a
type of technology out on the road?

1073
01:09:34,259 --> 01:09:38,195
<i>Alan Lloyd failed in his
leadership to really steer</i>

1074
01:09:38,263 --> 01:09:42,097
the zero emission vehicle mandate
toward a successful outcome.

1075
01:09:42,167 --> 01:09:43,634
Oh, I know Alec very well.

1076
01:09:43,702 --> 01:09:46,193
I know Alec very well. And we had some...

1077
01:09:46,271 --> 01:09:49,729
heartfelt memos come back.

1078
01:09:49,808 --> 01:09:53,335
And it pained me, because I
have the utmost respect for Alec.

1079
01:09:53,679 --> 01:09:58,207
And it pained me to be accused

1080
01:09:58,350 --> 01:10:01,410
of basically abanding
the battery electrics.

1081
01:10:01,753 --> 01:10:05,553
<i>In addition to his role as
chairman of the Air Resources Board,</i>

1082
01:10:05,691 --> 01:10:08,057
<i>Alan Lloyd had another position.</i>

1083
01:10:08,126 --> 01:10:11,994
<i>Just four months before the
meeting that killed the electric car,</i>

1084
01:10:12,330 --> 01:10:16,790
<i>Lloyd accepted the chairmanship
of the California Fuel Cell Partnership.</i>

1085
01:10:18,136 --> 01:10:20,297
<i>I've been involved with
hydrogen since the early 90's.</i>

1086
01:10:20,372 --> 01:10:24,832
When I became chair of ARB ten years
later, I knew a lot about hydrogen.

1087
01:10:25,010 --> 01:10:29,140
So for me, I'm very much
fact-technology driven.

1088
01:10:29,281 --> 01:10:33,012
Maybe you can say that's an asset
or a handicap in the terms of hydrogen

1089
01:10:33,085 --> 01:10:35,815
because I knew what could be done.

1090
01:10:44,596 --> 01:10:47,190
Excuse me while I watch
my baby get off here.

1091
01:10:47,265 --> 01:10:49,495
<i>Carmakers convinced California</i>

1092
01:10:49,568 --> 01:10:54,427
<i>that the facts supported the
development of hydrogen fuel cell vehicles.</i>

1093
01:10:54,740 --> 01:10:57,436
<i>Were they a better
option than electric cars?</i>

1094
01:10:58,043 --> 01:11:02,104
<i>Toyota's national manager of
advanced technologies, Bill Reinert,</i>

1095
01:11:02,180 --> 01:11:06,708
<i>took their prototype hydrogen
fuel cell SUV on a press tour.</i>

1096
01:11:06,985 --> 01:11:11,684
One of our customers didn't really like this
car anywhere nearly as much as the EV1.

1097
01:11:12,958 --> 01:11:16,985
And the reason was not because it
would have anything bad about the car,

1098
01:11:17,062 --> 01:11:18,689
the reason was because his EV1,

1099
01:11:18,764 --> 01:11:21,392
he could charge it at home,
charge it at work,

1100
01:11:21,466 --> 01:11:24,367
and even though it provided limited range,

1101
01:11:24,436 --> 01:11:27,633
he didn't have to worry about
getting his car charged up.

1102
01:11:27,706 --> 01:11:31,403
With this car, with a limited access
to a hydrogen filling station,

1103
01:11:31,476 --> 01:11:34,377
he said he'd spend his whole day
planning how to get hydrogen

1104
01:11:34,446 --> 01:11:35,470
in the car and how to get back.

1105
01:11:35,547 --> 01:11:37,242
It's growing humbly.

1106
01:11:37,315 --> 01:11:39,749
The more you know, the more you realize

1107
01:11:39,818 --> 01:11:43,515
you really don't know what
issues are going to be put forward.

1108
01:11:43,722 --> 01:11:45,383
The number one worst question is:

1109
01:11:45,457 --> 01:11:48,085
"When can...
When will that be on the market?"

1110
01:11:48,860 --> 01:11:52,227
When will that be on the market?
That's the worst question.

1111
01:11:52,464 --> 01:11:54,591
Consumers are probably
going to want to know

1112
01:11:54,666 --> 01:11:57,260
how long it would be for
this to be mass produced.

1113
01:11:57,335 --> 01:11:58,734
That's quite a ways off.

1114
01:11:58,804 --> 01:12:01,932
We've got some real technical issues
we've got to solve, with hydrogen storage

1115
01:12:02,007 --> 01:12:03,941
with durability,
with cost reduction.

1116
01:12:04,009 --> 01:12:06,477
Is it a practical solution at this point?

1117
01:12:06,578 --> 01:12:08,341
The cars have a limited range,

1118
01:12:08,413 --> 01:12:12,907
the durability of the car isn't very good...
Let me see, what else?

1119
01:12:12,984 --> 01:12:15,009
They don't do well in cold weather.

1120
01:12:15,086 --> 01:12:17,020
Other than that, they're great.

1121
01:12:17,455 --> 01:12:18,945
Have you ever been to a dog race?

1122
01:12:19,024 --> 01:12:21,857
There's the mechanical
rabbit that's out in front

1123
01:12:21,927 --> 01:12:23,986
and the dogs never quite reach it.

1124
01:12:24,062 --> 01:12:28,658
Well, the fuel cell is the equivalent
of that mechanical rabbit.

1125
01:12:28,800 --> 01:12:29,824
We're going for it.

1126
01:12:29,901 --> 01:12:34,964
For the last 15 years they've been telling
us the fuel cells are 10 to 15 years off.

1127
01:12:36,374 --> 01:12:37,363
<i>You're an oil company.</i>

1128
01:12:37,442 --> 01:12:39,600
<i>Your business is to be selling a fuel.</i>

1129
01:12:40,212 --> 01:12:42,646
They think that it's a long time off, 30 years,

1130
01:12:42,914 --> 01:12:44,575
and they want to have a product that sells.

1131
01:12:44,649 --> 01:12:46,742
From that point,
they're protecting themselves

1132
01:12:46,818 --> 01:12:50,117
but the other side is that
they're protecting the status quo.

1133
00:12:50,489 --> 01:12:53,118
<i>We see in Scientific American</i>

1134
01:12:53,191 --> 01:12:56,888
<i>a double page ad by
General Motors and Shell both</i>

1135
01:12:56,962 --> 01:12:59,396
<i>touting both the fuel cell
that General Motors is doing</i>

1136
01:12:59,464 --> 01:13:02,365
<i>and also Shell as a potential
supplier of hydrogen.</i>

1137
01:13:05,804 --> 01:13:10,366
<i>If hydrogen can do a better job
as an energy carrier than electricity,</i>

1138
01:13:10,542 --> 01:13:14,308
<i>then by gosh, it should
be the carrier of choice.</i>

1139
01:13:15,113 --> 01:13:17,308
The problem is, it's not even close.

1140
01:13:17,382 --> 01:13:20,010
How far would this car ride
on environmental fuel?

1141
01:13:20,085 --> 01:13:25,022
It's approximately about a 100-125 miles.

1142
01:13:25,257 --> 01:13:28,090
Good. Interesting.

1143
01:13:28,326 --> 01:13:32,353
<i>A fuel cell car powered by
hydrogen made with electricity</i>

1144
01:13:32,430 --> 01:13:37,197
<i>uses three to four times more
energy than a car powered by batteries.</i>

1145
01:13:38,103 --> 01:13:40,833
This is the beginning of a fantastic technology,

1146
01:13:40,906 --> 01:13:43,397
and thanks for having us out here.

1147
01:13:43,475 --> 01:13:45,705
We're going to look at
some other vehicles in a minute,

1148
01:13:45,777 --> 01:13:49,907
but, hydrogen is the way of the future.

1149
01:13:50,015 --> 01:13:53,416
<i>Today, there's a lot of
enthusiasm for hydrogen cars</i>

1150
01:13:53,685 --> 01:13:56,620
<i>but, I wrote the whole book
"The Hype About Hydrogen".</i>

1151
01:13:57,023 --> 01:14:01,615
I think it's pretty clear that hydrogen
is a much tougher alternative fuel

1152
01:14:01,693 --> 01:14:04,457
than any other alternative
fuel we've ever pursued.

1153
01:14:04,529 --> 01:14:06,497
<i>These are the five miracles that you need</i>

1154
01:14:06,564 --> 01:14:08,293
<i>for a successful hydrogen
car in the marketplace.</i>

1155
01:14:08,834 --> 01:14:12,329
<i>First, your average hydrogen
car costs a million dollars.</i>

1156
01:14:12,604 --> 01:14:13,730
<i>That's got to drop.</i>

1157
01:14:15,173 --> 01:14:19,837
<i>Second, no known material to humankind
can store enough hydrogen onboard the car</i>

1158
01:14:19,911 --> 01:14:21,401
<i>to give you the range people want.</i>

1159
01:14:21,781 --> 01:14:25,848
<i>Miracle number three.
The fuel is wildly expensive.</i>

1160
01:14:25,917 --> 01:14:30,877
<i>Even hydrogen from dirty fossil fuels
is 2 or 3 times more expensive than gasoline.</i>

1161
01:14:31,257 --> 01:14:34,691
<i>Fourth, you have to have
the fueling infrastructure.</i>

1162
01:14:34,759 --> 01:14:37,023
We have a 180 000 gas stations.

1163
01:14:37,095 --> 01:14:40,758
Someone's going to have to build at least
10 or 20 thousand hydrogen fueling stations

1164
01:14:40,832 --> 01:14:43,426
before anybody is going to be very interested.

1165
01:14:43,769 --> 01:14:46,127
<i>Miracle five is - you have to hope and pray</i>

1166
01:14:46,204 --> 01:14:49,696
<i>that the competitors in the
marketplace don't get any better.</i>

1167
01:14:49,774 --> 01:14:54,643
Because right now, the best car in
the marketplace just got a lot better,

1168
01:14:54,713 --> 01:14:55,737
the hybrid vehicle.

1169
01:14:56,081 --> 01:14:58,405
<i>Still runs on gasoline,
you can fuel it everywhere,</i>

1170
01:14:58,483 --> 01:15:00,178
<i>it has twice the range of a regular car.</i>

1171
01:15:00,386 --> 01:15:03,115
<i>Current hybrid vehicles
depend on gasoline,</i>

1172
01:15:04,255 --> 01:15:07,713
<i>but use an electric motor
to increase their fuel economy.</i>

1173
01:15:07,792 --> 01:15:11,855
<i>And if battery technology
keeps getting steadily better,</i>

1174
01:15:12,597 --> 01:15:16,897
<i>than the best hybrid, and then
plug-in hybrid in the year 2020</i>

1175
01:15:16,968 --> 01:15:20,734
will be vastly superior
to the best hydrogen car.

1176
01:15:22,140 --> 01:15:25,507
You guys have filmed me long enought to know

1177
01:15:25,577 --> 01:15:28,740
that I'm not going to
dance around the issue.

1178
01:15:28,813 --> 01:15:32,271
And these could be a
long ways out into the future.

1179
01:15:34,819 --> 01:15:37,617
Toyota says: "Fuel cell
cars, 30 years away."

1180
01:15:37,689 --> 01:15:40,886
Then I get the calls from the Department
of Energy and the State of California:

1181
01:15:40,959 --> 01:15:42,221
"What the hell are you doing?"

1182
01:15:42,293 --> 01:15:44,591
And all the other fuel cell manufacturers:

1183
01:15:44,662 --> 01:15:48,393
"We're trying to make a living here..."

1184
01:15:48,466 --> 01:15:49,728
It's awful.

1185
01:15:50,869 --> 01:15:53,838
<i>Just because a lot of people
want it to work, it's no guarantee.</i>

1186
01:15:53,905 --> 01:15:56,772
That's Disneyland, you know -
wishing makes it come true.

1187
01:15:56,841 --> 01:15:58,934
I don't work in Disneyland.

1188
01:15:59,277 --> 01:16:01,939
I work in the real world, where
wishing doesn't make it come true

1189
01:16:02,013 --> 01:16:05,949
and you really have to work hard
to make it come true. Hopefully we do.

1190
01:16:13,191 --> 01:16:18,185
<i>On the 27th day of their vigil,
activists finally heard from GM.</i>

1191
01:16:27,539 --> 01:16:31,771
Paul Scott called: "Are you guys busy?
They're hauling in the cars right now."

1192
01:16:31,843 --> 01:16:34,403
<i>"GM is loading the cars
on trucks right now!"</i>

1193
01:16:34,479 --> 01:16:35,468
"What, what?"

1194
01:16:35,547 --> 01:16:38,710
"Yeah, we'll drop everything
and run on out there right now."

1195
01:16:45,924 --> 01:16:47,516
They've loaded them up,

1196
01:16:47,592 --> 01:16:50,652
tires screeching, and panels
cracking against each other

1197
01:16:50,728 --> 01:16:52,889
as they shoved them onto the tracks.

1198
01:16:57,802 --> 01:17:00,032
<i>We're up against most
of the money in the world.</i>

1199
01:17:00,105 --> 01:17:03,404
We're up against the oil industry,
the automobile industry.

1200
01:17:03,808 --> 01:17:08,336
<i>It's David versus Goliath
in a very big way</i>

1201
01:17:09,114 --> 01:17:12,777
but if there are enough
Davids in the world, we can win.

1202
01:17:20,225 --> 01:17:22,557
<i>GM, shame on you!</i>

1203
01:17:25,563 --> 01:17:29,431
<i>General Motors is taking the EV1's out of here,</i>

1204
01:17:29,934 --> 01:17:31,265
<i>destroying them,</i>

1205
01:17:31,336 --> 01:17:33,497
<i>doing the work of the oil companies.</i>

1206
01:17:34,839 --> 01:17:38,172
We're going to ask you guys just
to give us some grass area

1207
01:17:38,243 --> 01:17:40,234
If you could just get out
of the driveway for us

1208
01:17:40,311 --> 01:17:43,439
so we don't have to put
cuffs on anybody. Thank you.

1209
01:18:07,739 --> 01:18:09,570
Don't crush the EV1.

1210
01:18:25,123 --> 01:18:31,255
<i>On March 15th, 2005,
the last EV1's in the Burbank lot</i>

1211
01:18:31,329 --> 01:18:33,490
<i>were taken away and destroyed.</i>

1212
01:19:39,899 --> 01:19:42,762
- Alright, come on in.
- Cool.

1213
01:19:42,834 --> 01:19:45,428
We'll go down to the vault
and I'll show you the car.

1214
01:19:46,971 --> 01:19:48,370
I miss this little car.

1215
01:19:48,439 --> 01:19:50,873
Yeah. We love having it.

1216
01:19:50,942 --> 01:19:54,070
We have a number of electric
vehicles in the collection, and the hybrids,

1217
01:19:54,145 --> 01:19:56,477
but we're especially happy about this.

1218
01:19:57,815 --> 01:19:59,840
This is a special one.

1219
01:20:00,451 --> 01:20:03,284
- There she is.
- My baby!

1220
01:20:08,660 --> 01:20:09,752
Number 99.

1221
01:20:11,429 --> 01:20:14,262
- You might recognize this car.
- I do. It was Chris's car.

1222
01:20:14,332 --> 01:20:15,424
Sure was.

1223
01:20:17,969 --> 01:20:19,197
Please, have a seat.

1224
01:20:19,270 --> 01:20:22,000
There's only one challenge,
it doesn't start up.

1225
01:20:23,374 --> 01:20:26,366
You know that General Motors disabled them.

1226
01:20:26,444 --> 01:20:28,708
- I know.
- We wish they didn't, but they had to.

1227
01:20:28,780 --> 01:20:30,941
So we understand that.
We're just happy to have it.

1228
01:20:31,015 --> 01:20:32,004
Yeah.

1229
01:20:32,283 --> 01:20:34,615
That is such an important
part of automotive history.

1230
01:20:34,686 --> 01:20:36,153
- It is...
- To have a manufacturer like

1231
01:20:36,220 --> 01:20:39,280
General Motors participate
in this program. It's wonderful.

1232
01:20:39,357 --> 01:20:42,588
The thing is, it shouldn't be
a part of automotive history.

1233
01:20:59,444 --> 01:21:02,545
Ever since 1939, they
would dangle this electric car.

1234
01:21:03,081 --> 01:21:04,514
They'd have a few models out there.

1235
01:21:04,582 --> 01:21:07,073
They'd say that's something
in another few years.

1236
01:21:07,151 --> 01:21:09,984
And it never came. Because
they never intended it to come.

1237
01:21:10,054 --> 01:21:13,182
They make too much money
with the technological stagnation

1238
01:21:13,257 --> 01:21:14,815
in the internal combustion engine.

1239
01:21:18,796 --> 01:21:23,199
If somethin becomes scarce, then there's
economic pressures to find alternatives.

1240
01:21:23,301 --> 01:21:25,769
And as long as no alternatives exist,

1241
01:21:26,371 --> 01:21:29,499
the scarce item can become
increasingly profitable.

1242
01:21:33,811 --> 01:21:36,006
These are the same batteries that
are used in your laptop computer.

1243
01:21:36,080 --> 01:21:38,674
We have 6800 cells.

1244
01:21:38,750 --> 01:21:41,412
And it can go 300 miles on one charge,

1245
01:21:41,719 --> 01:21:43,710
running along at 70 mph.

1246
01:21:43,888 --> 01:21:46,379
It's now 0-60 in 3.6 seconds.

1247
01:21:47,458 --> 01:21:50,757
It's an amazing performance for
any car, not just an electric car.

1248
01:21:50,828 --> 01:21:52,386
<i>Those same batteries could be put in EV1</i>

1249
01:21:52,463 --> 01:21:55,091
and make it a 300-mile-range car very easily.

1250
01:21:55,666 --> 01:21:58,726
It's a shame seeing these cars destroyed
when you could upgrade them.

1251
01:22:01,773 --> 01:22:04,003
I know what I did and why I did it.

1252
01:22:04,308 --> 01:22:07,539
And if I had to do the same
thing again based on the data,

1253
01:22:07,678 --> 01:22:09,077
and I've seen what has happened to date,

1254
01:22:09,147 --> 01:22:11,115
I would do exactly the same thing.

1255
01:22:14,452 --> 01:22:16,784
When we talk about sensible energy policy

1256
01:22:16,854 --> 01:22:20,017
most people hear is: "You're going
to make me drive a small car,

1257
01:22:20,091 --> 01:22:21,854
"you're going to make
me keep my house cold,

1258
01:22:21,926 --> 01:22:24,019
"and essentially, you're going
to make me live like a European."

1259
01:22:28,766 --> 01:22:30,597
It's a lack of leadership.

1260
01:22:30,902 --> 01:22:34,429
It's a lack of being able
to take on the oil industry,

1261
01:22:34,639 --> 01:22:36,698
and the automobile industry,

1262
01:22:36,774 --> 01:22:39,106
and recognize that they are not Uncle Sam.

1263
01:22:39,177 --> 01:22:41,338
Uncle Sam has to be Uncle Sam,

1264
01:22:41,446 --> 01:22:44,006
and Uncle Sam is acting
like they're General Motors.

1265
01:22:47,718 --> 01:22:50,448
They're squandering
huge amounts of money

1266
01:22:50,521 --> 01:22:54,150
on hydrogen cars, which,
by any reasonable estimate,

1267
01:22:54,225 --> 01:22:56,591
are not going to be
selling in the consumer market

1268
01:22:56,661 --> 01:22:58,993
for two decades at the earliest.

1269
01:22:59,096 --> 01:23:02,031
<i>I think it will go down as
one of the biggest blunders</i>

1270
01:23:02,099 --> 01:23:04,567
<i>in the history of the automotive industry.</i>

1271
01:23:08,906 --> 01:23:12,398
Have you never heard that expression:
"Death by a million cuts"?

1272
01:23:12,477 --> 01:23:15,742
Little tiny cuts, eventually
someone will bleed to death.

1273
01:23:19,050 --> 01:23:23,578
<i>The fight over electric cars was
quite simply, a fight about the future.</i>

1274
01:23:24,655 --> 01:23:29,217
<i>Goliath won this round, but
now Goliath has new problems.</i>

1275
01:23:30,094 --> 01:23:32,528
<i>Oil prices have soared.</i>

1276
01:23:32,597 --> 01:23:35,896
<i>America is further
entangled in the Middle East,</i>

1277
01:23:36,801 --> 01:23:40,066
<i>and global warming is an
increasingly serious threat.</i>

1278
01:23:40,705 --> 01:23:43,469
<i>What can we do to reshape the future?</i>

1279
01:23:43,541 --> 01:23:47,671
<i>This city is replete with famous
names that are no longer here.</i>

1280
01:23:48,846 --> 01:23:52,174
<i>Why? Because they
couldn't adapt to change.</i>

1281
01:23:52,683 --> 01:23:54,545
We all have to adapt to change.

1282
01:23:55,086 --> 01:23:58,454
<i>Don't debate about
who's to blame or what to blame.</i>

1283
01:23:58,723 --> 01:24:00,315
Let's build new industries.

1284
01:24:00,391 --> 01:24:02,757
Let's make America strong again.

1285
01:24:03,060 --> 01:24:07,190
<i>Chelsea continues her work with
a new group called Plug In America,</i>

1286
01:24:07,398 --> 01:24:09,696
<i>working with citizens
across the political spectrum</i>

1287
01:24:09,767 --> 01:24:12,702
<i>to promote an independant energy future.</i>

1288
01:24:13,304 --> 01:24:16,330
I met Jim Woolsey at an
event, and as it turns out

1289
01:24:16,407 --> 01:24:18,739
he was already a bit of a fan
of stuff that we were doing,

1290
01:24:18,809 --> 01:24:21,039
<i>and he's come to work
with Plug In America.</i>

1291
01:24:21,112 --> 01:24:24,775
That's one example of the types
of relationships that have to exist

1292
01:24:24,849 --> 01:24:27,044
in order to further what we all want.

1293
01:24:27,352 --> 01:24:32,413
I've served in four administrations,
with presidential appointments,

1294
01:24:32,490 --> 01:24:35,687
<i>all in different aspects
of national security.</i>

1295
01:24:35,760 --> 01:24:38,593
And the fact that two thirds of
the world's proven reserves of oil

1296
01:24:38,663 --> 01:24:42,064
are in the Middle East, and that we're
so dependant on that part of our world,

1297
01:24:42,133 --> 01:24:44,624
<i>is a very big national security question.</i>

1298
01:24:45,369 --> 01:24:46,768
Behind me there are two things.

1299
01:24:46,837 --> 01:24:50,398
One is a Prius, hybrid
gasoline-electric Toyota,

1300
01:24:50,708 --> 01:24:52,767
<i>and an electrical substation.</i>

1301
01:24:52,843 --> 01:24:55,107
<i>Today, they don't have
much to do with one another,</i>

